snippet.title: Design Council: Design vs. styling
snippet.description: Ask automotive designers what the requirements are for someone in their position and you won't hear the word "styling." In fact, the word has such negative connotations it's probably long been removed from their lexicon.

snippet.title: Design Council: Range Rover
snippet.description: Eric Gallina takes us through the many faces of the most capable luxury ride on the planet.

snippet.title: 9-year-old's school dinner blog shut down by council
snippet.description: A charity-fundraising primary school girl has been banned from blogging about her school dinners by the mean old local council in Scotland.

snippet.title: City Council paper usage down 40 percent after switch to iPads
snippet.description: The City Council of Vancouver, Wash., reports that in the two months following a switch to iPads, paper usage is down by nearly 40 percent.

snippet.title: Identity Theft Council launches in Bay Area
snippet.description: Grassroots group helps train volunteers to counsel identity fraud victims.

snippet.title: LA City Council delays Google Apps decision
snippet.description: Adopting Google Apps would cost the city of Los Angeles more than continuing on with its current e-mail system, prompting a budget committee to ask for more details.

snippet.title: Hacker named to Homeland Security Advisory Council
snippet.description: Hacker and Defcon founder Jeff Moss joins former FBI, CIA directors on Homeland Security Advisory Council.

snippet.title: Blogging best practice council should have blogged their announcement
snippet.description: [Ironic announcement alert] Oh, hey, let's start a blog council but not have a blog!

snippet.title: Google points to Iowa for sowing satellite antenna farm
snippet.description: If approved by the FCC, Google's satellite dishes could get feeds from broadcast networks and even be bundled with the company's high-speed Internet service.

snippet.title: 27,000 Google Chromebooks headed to U.S. schools
snippet.description: Google has found allies in three school districts that will bring the browser-based laptops to thousands of students. At least some of those kids not-so-secretly covet tablets, though.
